                  Law 25/03: "Sasaki cemented a legacy while he was still in high school. There was a stretch when he was asked to throw nearly 500 pitches..."
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapseOne" class="accordion-collapse collapse show" aria-labelledby="headingOne" data-bs-parent="#analysisAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  Sasaki cemented a legacy while he was still in high school. There was a stretch when he was asked to throw nearly 500 pitches in a week's time during the prestigious Koshien tournament. He has a fastball that can touch 101 mph and has sat 97-99 in shorter bursts. The pitch, which he throws from a three-quarters arm slot, features modest arm-side run and, when thrown to the top of the zone, ride through the zone. He complements the fastball with a splitter that features significant vertical drop due to his release point, sitting in the high-80s. The pitch plays in the zone as a strike and can generate whiffs below the zone. The third offering is a low-80s slider with vertical tilt that he commands well within the zone.
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingTwo">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseTwo" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseTwo">
                  McDaniel 25/03: "In high school, Anthony presented clubs with a risky but exciting combination of present raw power and long-term power projection, but..."
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapseTwo" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingTwo" data-bs-parent="#analysisAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  In high school, Anthony presented clubs with a risky but exciting combination of present raw power and long-term power projection, but the hit tool needed some work. Anthony has shown glimpses of being able to lift the ball, but his best trait is his high-end exit velocity, with a max EV of 109 mph. His minor league track record includes an encouraging rise, from a 66 wRC+ in Low-A to 102 in High-A, and then a 142 in a half-season at Double-A. He also has hit nine homers in 160 AFL at-bats over two autumns and posted solid walk rates in 2023, particularly at Double-A.
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="accordion-item">
              <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingThree">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseThree" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseThree">
                  Longenhagen 25/03: "Because his fastball is so well-located, it plays as an out pitch even though it doesn't have exceptional velocity or movement..."
                </button>
              </h2>
              <div id="collapseThree" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingThree" data-bs-parent="#analysisAccordion">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                  Because his fastball is so well-located, it plays as an out pitch even though it doesn't have exceptional velocity or movement. Gray sits 92-95 and touches 96 mph, and the pitch has a little bit of tail. But that tail is suppressed because Gray is typically working east/west with his heater, living at the edges of the zone rather than elevating. He has a full repertoire of secondaries, headlined by a hellacious overhand curveball in the low-80s. It's a hammer with significant depth and often buckles hitters. Gray commands it with consistency, which is abnormal for pitchers with this sort of arm slot and curveball shape.
                </div>
